---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Install MyUsage — macOS menu bar app"
  description="Step-by-step install guide for MyUsage. Download from GitHub Releases, drag to /Applications, work around the Gatekeeper warning on first launch."
>
  <h1>Install</h1>
  <p>
    MyUsage ships as a standard macOS <code>.app</code> bundle delivered through
    GitHub Releases. There's no installer; the install is one drag.
  </p>

  <h2>1 · Download</h2>
  <p>
    Grab the latest <code>MyUsage-&lt;version&gt;.zip</code> from the
    <a href="https://github.com/zchan0/MyUsage/releases/latest">latest release page</a>.
    Each release also has a <code>.sha256</code> file you can verify against:
  </p>
  <pre><code>shasum -a 256 -c MyUsage-0.9.1.zip.sha256</code></pre>

  <h2>2 · Move to /Applications</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Unzip <code>MyUsage-0.9.1.zip</code> (Finder will do this automatically when you double-click).</li>
    <li>Drag <code>MyUsage.app</code> into <code>/Applications/</code>.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>3 · First launch (Gatekeeper)</h2>
  <p>
    MyUsage is ad-hoc signed — there's no paid Apple Developer certificate
    yet. macOS will warn the first time you open it that the developer
    can't be verified. There are two ways through:
  </p>

  <h3>Option A — Right-click → Open</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>In Finder, right-click (or control-click) <code>MyUsage.app</code>.</li>
    <li>Choose <strong>Open</strong>.</li>
    <li>The dialog will offer an <strong>Open</strong> button (greyed out the first time you saw it; available now).</li>
  </ol>
  <p>macOS remembers this decision; subsequent launches are normal.</p>

  <h3>Option B — Strip the quarantine attribute</h3>
  <p>
    If you prefer the terminal, this clears the quarantine flag and opens the app:
  </p>
  <pre><code>xattr -cr /Applications/MyUsage.app && open /Applications/MyUsage.app</code></pre>

  <div class="callout">
    <b>Why the warning?</b> Apple's notarization service requires a paid
    Apple Developer Program membership ($99/year). MyUsage is currently
    ad-hoc signed only. The warning is cosmetic — the binary itself is the
    one published in GitHub Releases, and you can verify with the SHA-256.
    Notarization is on the roadmap.
  </div>

  <h2>4 · Per-provider auth</h2>
  <p>
    Once MyUsage is running, click the menu bar icon and you'll see
    cards for each provider. The status of each card depends on whether
    that provider's auth artifact is present on this Mac:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Claude Code</strong> reads <code>~/.claude/.credentials.json</code> (or the matching Keychain entry). Sign in to Claude Code at least once and the credentials appear automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Codex</strong> reads <code>~/.codex/auth.json</code>. Same pattern — sign in to the Codex CLI once and you're set.</li>
    <li><strong>Cursor</strong> reads its local <code>state.vscdb</code> SQLite store under <code>~/Library/Application Support/Cursor/</code>. Just being signed in to the Cursor app is enough.</li>
    <li><strong>Antigravity</strong> probes the running language server process. The card shows <code>IDE off</code> when Antigravity isn't running, <code>LIVE</code> when it is.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>5 · (Optional) Multi-device sync</h2>
  <p>
    Open <strong>Settings → General</strong>, click <strong>Choose…</strong>
    next to "Sync folder", and pick a folder that's already syncing across
    your Macs (iCloud Drive's <code>Mobile Documents</code> folder works
    out of the box). Repeat the same selection on every Mac. Within one
    refresh cycle, each Mac's monthly cost row will show the aggregate
    across all of them.
  </p>
  <p>
    The full design — including the device-ID derivation and how to forget
    retired peers — is in the <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/docs/multi-device-sync`}>multi-device sync doc</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Updating</h2>
  <p>
    MyUsage checks GitHub Releases on launch. When a newer version is
    published, the popover header gets a small dot, and Settings → About
    surfaces a download banner. The banner can fetch the new
    <code>.zip</code> for you and open Finder pre-positioned for the drag
    into <code>/Applications</code>. No auto-install yet — staying explicit
    until notarization lands.
  </p>

  <h2>Uninstall</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Quit MyUsage from its popover (gear icon → Quit).</li>
    <li>Drag <code>/Applications/MyUsage.app</code> to the Trash.</li>
    <li>Optional: remove preferences with <code>defaults delete com.zchan0.MyUsage</code> and the sync data with <code>rm -rf &lt;your-sync-folder&gt;/devices/&lt;deviceID&gt;</code>.</li>
  </ol>
</Layout>
